#Text=0H WILLIE WE HAVE MISSED YOU.
#Text=Oh!
#Text=Willie we hare missed yon, For you hare tamed long; We’ve not enjoyed a single meal.
#Text=Nor heard the evening song.
#Text=Teu went away at early morn, But where you did hot say.
#Text=And sad were all our anxious hearts At closing of the day.
#Text=The gloomy night kept wearing on.
#Text=And still you did not come— Oh !
#Text=Willie we have missed you.
#Text=Welcome, welcome home.* But what is this that movesroe, And startles my repose ?
#Text=Yon cannot be my Willie dear.
#Text=Ton wear not Willies clothes.
#Text=Ah!
#Text=now I see with joy and pride, You’ve joined the rifle corps, Prepared to hold your liberty.
#Text=As our fathers did of yore.
#Text=I do not wish that you should be Compelled from me to roam— OhWillie you have pleased me, Welcome, welcome home.
#Text=But who has been your tailor To deck you out so gay, So bravely and becomingly In soldier-like array?
#Text=Tour clothes are made with taste and skill.
#Text=The fabric good also; And manfully you’ll lock, my love, If to the field you go.
#Text=But oh, I should be very sad If were compelled to part— Oh!
#Text=Willie I should miss you, The comfort of my heart Dear love, our honest tailor Lives in our own good town, And for his skill and promptitude Has won a just renown.
#Text=For cheapness he is not excelled— The best that eer was worn, By soldier or civilian, Is the clothing of KILLOHN.
#Text=His mart is now threefold enlarged.
#Text=And grand is the display, So there the people all should haste Without the least delay.
#Text=KILLORN AND CO., ARMY TAILORS, AND GENERAL OUTFITTERS, Nos. 11 and 13, George street, and No. 2, Wellington-street, near the Marketplace, Ashton-under-Lyue.
